PythonJava Python<pre><code>print("hello world")
</code></pre> Java<pre><code>public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("hello world");
    }
}
</code></pre> <ol> <li>All code in Java must be part of a class.</li> <li>We delimit the beginning and end of segments of code with <code>{}</code>.</li> <li>All statements in Java must end with a semicolon.</li> <li>For code to run, we need <code>public static void main(String[] args)</code>.</li> </ol> <p>Running a Java Program Bash<pre><code>$ javac HelloWorld.java
$ java HelloWorld
Hello World!
</code></pre></p>

PythonJava Python<pre><code>x = 0
while x &lt; 10:
    print(x)
    x = x + 1
</code></pre> Java<pre><code>public class HelloNumbers {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int x = 0;
        while (x &lt; 10) {
            System.out.println(x);
            x = x + 1;
        }
    }
}
</code></pre> <ol> <li>Before Java variables can be used, they must be declared.</li> <li>Java variables must have a specific type.</li> </ol>

PythonJava Python<pre><code>def larger(x, y):
    if x &gt; y:
        return x
    return y

print(larger(5, -10))
</code></pre> Java<pre><code>public static int larger(int x, int y) {
    if (x &gt; y) {
        return x;
    }
    return y;
}
</code></pre> <ol> <li>Java functions must specify the return type.</li> <li>Java functions must declare the type of each parameter.</li> </ol>
